#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:344
msgid "Commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:346
msgid "Routinator provides a number of operations around the local RPKI repository. These can be requested by providing different commands on the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:351
msgid "Prepares the local repository directories and the TAL directory for running Routinator.  Specifically,  makes sure the local repository directory exists, and creates the TAL directory and fills it with the TALs of the five RIRs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:356
msgid "For more information about TALs, see `Trust Anchor Locators`_ below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:360
msgid "Forces installation of the TALs even if the TAL directory already exists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:365
msgid "Before you can use the ARIN TAL, you need to agree to the ARIN Relying Party Agreement (RPA). You can find it at https://www.arin.net/resources/manage/rpki/rpa.pdf and explicitly agree to it via this option. This explicit agreement is necessary in order to install the ARIN TAL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:373
msgid "If, after reading the ARIN Relying Party Agreement, you decide you do not or cannot agree to it, this option allows you to skip installation of the ARIN TAL. Note that this means Routinator will not have access to any information published for resources assigned under ARIN."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:382
msgid "This command requests that Routinator update the local repository and then validate the Route Origin Attestations in the repository and output the valid route origins, which are also known as Validated ROA Payload or VRPs, as a list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:389
msgid "Specifies the output file to write the list to. If this option is missing or file is - the list is printed to standard output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:394
msgid "The output format to use. Routinator currently supports the following formats:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:405
msgid "csv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:398
msgid "The list is formatted as lines of comma-separated values of the prefix in slash notation, the maximum prefix length, the autonomous system number, and an abbreviation for the trust anchor the entry is derived from. The latter is the name of the TAL file without the extension *.tal*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:404
msgid "This is the default format used if the :option:`-f` option is missing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:411
msgid "csvcompat"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:408
msgid "The same as csv except that all fields are embedded in double quotes and the autonomous system number is given without the prefix AS. This format is pretty much identical to the CSV produced by the RIPE NCC Validator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:424
msgid "csvext"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:414
msgid "An extended version of csv each line contains these comma-separated values: the rsync URI of the ROA the line is taken from (or \"N/A\" if it isn't from a ROA), the autonomous system number, the prefix in slash notation, the maximum prefix length, the not-before date and not-after date of the validity of the ROA."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:421
msgid "This format was used in the RIPE NCC RPKI Validator version 1. That version produces one file per trust anchor. This is not currently supported by Routinator -- all entries will be in one single output file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:438
msgid "json"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:427
msgid "The list is placed into a JSON object with a single element *roas* which contains an array of objects with four elements each:  The autonomous system number of the network authorized to originate a prefix in *asn*, the prefix in slash notation in *prefix*, the maximum prefix length of the announced route in *maxLength*, and the trust anchor from which the authorization was derived in *ta*. This format is identical to that produced by the RIPE NCC RPKI Validator except for different naming of the trust anchor. Routinator uses the name of the TAL file without the extension *.tal* whereas the RIPE NCC Validator has a dedicated name for each."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:442
msgid "openbgpd"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:441
msgid "Choosing this format causes Routinator to produce a roa- set configuration item for the OpenBGPD configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:446
msgid "bird"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:445
msgid "Choosing this format causes Routinator to produce a roa table configuration item for the BIRD configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:450
msgid "bird2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:449
msgid "Choosing this format causes Routinator to produce a roa table configuration item for the BIRD2 configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:457
msgid "rpsl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:453
msgid "This format produces a list of RPSL objects with the authorization in the fields *route*, *origin*, and *source*. In addition, the fields *descr*, *mnt-by*, *created*, and *last-modified*, are present with more or less meaningful values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:464
msgid "summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:460
msgid "This format produces a summary of the content of the RPKI repository. For each trust anchor, it will print the number of verified ROAs and VRPs. Note that this format does not take filters into account. It will always provide numbers for the complete repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:466
msgid "none"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:467
msgid "This format produces no output whatsoever."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:471
msgid "The repository will not be updated before producing the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:475
#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:528
#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:672
msgid "If any of the rsync commands needed to update the repository failed, Routinator completes the operation and exits with status code 2. Normally, it would exit with status code 0 indicating success."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:481
msgid "Only output VRPs for the given ASN. The option can be given multiple times, in which case VRPs for all provided ASNs are provided. ASNs can be given with or without the prefix AS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:487
msgid "Only output VRPs with an address prefix that covers the given prefix, i.e., whose prefix is equal to or less specific than the given prefix. This will include VRPs regardless of their ASN and max length.  In other words, the output will include all VRPs that need to be considered when deciding whether an announcement for the prefix is RPKI valid or invalid."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:494
msgid "The option can be given multiple times, in which case VRPs for all prefixes are provided. It can also be combined with one or more ASN filters. Then all matching VRPs are included. That is, filters combine as \"or\" not \"and.\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:502
msgid "This command can be used to perform RPKI route origin validation for a route announcement.  Routinator will determine whether the provided announcement is RPKI valid, invalid, or not found."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:508
msgid "The AS number of the autonomous system that originated the route announcement. ASNs can be given with or without the prefix AS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:513
msgid "The address prefix the route announcement is for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:517
msgid "A detailed analysis on the reasoning behind the validation is printed in JSON format including lists of the VPRs that caused the particular result.   If this option is omitted, Routinator will only print the determined state."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:524
msgid "The repository will not be updated before performing validation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:536
msgid "This command causes Routinator to act as a server for the RPKI-to-Router (RTR) and HTTP protocols. In this mode, Routinator will read all the TALs (See `Trust Anchor Locators`_ below) and will stay attached to the terminal unless the :option:`-d` option is given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:541
msgid "The server will periodically update the local repository, every ten minutes by default, notify any clients of changes, and let them fetch validated data. It will not, however, reread the trust anchor locators. Thus, if you update them, you will have to restart Routinator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:546
msgid "You can provide a number of addresses and ports to listen on for RTR and HTTP through command line options or their configuration file equivalent. Currently, Routinator will only start listening on these ports after an initial validation run has finished."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:551
msgid "It will not listen on any sockets unless explicitly specified. It will still run and periodically update the repository. This might be useful for use with :subcmd:`vrps` mode with the :option:`-n` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:557
msgid "If present, Routinator will detach from the terminal after a successful start."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:562
msgid "Specifies a local address and port to listen on for incoming RTR connections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:565
msgid "Routinator supports both protocol version 0 defined in :rfc:`6810` and version 1 defined in :rfc:`8210`. However, it does not support router keys introduced in version 1.  IPv6 addresses must be enclosed in square brackets. You can provide the option multiple times to let Routinator listen on multiple address-port pairs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:573
msgid "Specifies the address and port to listen on for incoming HTTP connections.  See `HTTP Service`_ below for more information on the HTTP service provided by Routinator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:579
msgid "The RTR listening socket will be acquired from systemd via socket activation. Use this option together with systemd's socket units to allow a Routinator running as a regular user to bind to the default RTR port 323."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:584
msgid "Currently, all TCP listener sockets handed over by systemd will be used for the RTR protocol."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:589
msgid "The amount of seconds the server should wait after having finished updating and validating the local repository before starting to update again. The next update will be earlier if objects in the repository expire earlier. The default value is 600 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:596
msgid "The amount of seconds to suggest to an RTR client to wait before trying to request data again if that failed. The default value is 600 seconds, as recommended in :rfc:`8210`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:602
msgid "The amount of seconds to an RTR client can keep using data if it cannot refresh it. After that time, the client should discard the data. Note that this value was introduced in version 1 of the RTR protocol and is thus not relevant for clients that only implement version 0. The default value, as recommended in :rfc:`8210`, is 7200 seconds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:611
msgid "In RTR, a client can request to only receive the changes that happened since the last version of the data it had seen. This option sets how many change sets the server will at most keep. If a client requests changes from an older version, it will get the current full set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:617
msgid "Note that routers typically stay connected with their RTR server and therefore really only ever need one single change set. Additionally, if RTR server or router are restarted, they will have a new session with new change sets and need to exchange a full data set, too. Thus, increasing the value probably only ever increases memory consumption."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:624
msgid "The default value is 10."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:628
msgid "States a file which will be used in daemon mode to store the processes PID.  While the process is running, it will keep the file locked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:634
msgid "The working directory for the daemon process. In daemon mode, Routinator will change to this directory while detaching from the terminal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:640
msgid "The root directory for the daemon process. If this option is provided, the daemon process will change its root directory to the given directory. This will only work if all other paths provided via the configuration or command line options are under this directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:648
msgid "The name of the user to change to for the daemon process. It this option is provided, Routinator will run as that user after the listening sockets for HTTP and RTR have been created. The option has no effect unless :option:`--detach` is also used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:655
msgid "The name of the group to change to for the daemon process.  It this option is provided, Routinator will run as that group after the listening sockets for HTTP and RTR have been created.  The option has no effect unless :option:`--detach` is also used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:662
msgid "Updates the local repository by resyncing all known publication points. The command will also validate the updated repository to discover any new publication points that appear in the repository and fetch their data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:667
msgid "As such, the command really is a shortcut for running :command:`routinator` :subcmd:`vrps` :option:`-f` ``none``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:679
msgid "Displays the manual page, i.e., this page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:683
msgid "If this option is provided, the manual page will be written to the given file instead of displaying it. Use - to output the manual page to standard output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:688
msgid "Trust Anchor Locators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:689
msgid "RPKI uses trust anchor locators, or TALs, to identify the location and public keys of the trusted root CA certificates. Routinator keeps these TALs in files in the TAL directory which can be set by the  :option:`-t` option. If the :option:`-b` option is used instead, the TAL directory will be in the subdirectory *tals* under the directory specified in this option. The default location, if no options are used at all is :file:`$HOME/.rpki-cache/tals`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:696
msgid "This directory can be created and populated with the TALs of the five Regional Internet Registries (RIRs) via the :command:`init` command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:699
msgid "If the directory does exist, Routinator will use all files with an extension of *.tal* in this directory. This means that you can add and remove trust anchors by adding and removing files in this directory. If you add files, make sure they are in the format described by :rfc:`7730` or the upcoming :rfc:`8630`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:708
msgid "Configuration File"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:709
msgid "Instead of providing all options on the command line, they can also be provided through a configuration file. Such a file can be selected through the :option:`-c` option. If no configuration file is specified this way but a file named :file:`$HOME/.routinator.conf` is present, this file is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:714
msgid "The configuration file is a file in TOML format. In short, it consists of a sequence of key-value pairs, each on its own line. Strings are to be enclosed in double quotes. Lists can be given by enclosing a comma-separated list of values in square brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:719
msgid "The configuration file can contain the following entries. All path values are interpreted relative to the directory the configuration file is located in. All values can be overridden via the command line options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:725
msgid "repository-dir"
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:724
msgid "A string containing the path to the directory to store the local repository in. This entry is mandatory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../routinator/manual-page.rst:729
msgid "tal-dir"
